	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New Orleans</placeName> <date>March 1. 1854</date>.</p>
				<p><addressee>Rev. I. Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Dear Friend&#44;</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">You will probably chide me for<lb/> not having sent you my little funeral address spoken<lb/> at the <add>&#63;</add> of the late <persName>Mr. Touro</persName>.  The truth is I preferred<lb/> reading your own remarks&#44; which I am fully assured&#44;<lb/> will be more gratifying to your readers.  The Asmonean<lb/> I perceive has published <persName>Clapp&#39;s</persName> sermon in full&#44;<lb/> and a most wretched production of a rhymester<lb/> which&#44; to save the credit of Jewish talent ought<lb/> to have been suppressed.  What do you think<lb/> the author of it has even the ineffable conceit<lb/> to send it to <persName>Mr Shepperd</persName> and ask for his<lb/> patronage&#33;  And thus it has been a subject of<lb/> ridicule in the Picaynue<add>&#63;</add> of this city.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Regarding the transmission of the<lb/> remains of your late venerable friend&#44; <persName>Mr. G.<lb/> Kursheedt</persName> will no doubt have advised you.<lb/>  It will not take place before <date>July</date> next.  <persName>Mr.<lb/> K.</persName> has the sole management of the whole affair&#59;<lb/> a rather delicate duty is thus devolving upon<lb/> him.  The question will not be&#44; how much<lb/> shall be done&#44; but how little of the num&#45;</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>numerous resolutions adopted by various bodies<lb/> at the <placeName>North</placeName> shall be carried into effect.  There<lb/> can be no separate action allowed&#44; and the prob&#45;<lb/>ability is that&#44; in endeavouring to give satisfaction<lb/> to all&#44; <sic>offence</sic> may be taken in some quarter.  I<lb/> shall be satisfied with whatever arrangements<lb/> will be made&#59; tho&#39; as yet I do not even know&#44;<lb/> whether I shall be permitted to be present.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I am really sorry to hear you speak in<lb/> so despondent a strain.  Is there nothing in your<lb/> present independent position to counterbalance the<lb/> unjust treatment you have experienced&#63;  Think<lb/> for a moment&#44; you were to deliver a sermon &#8220;On<lb/> the disappointments incident to human life.&#8221;<lb/>  Would it not be a principal point&#44; to exhort your<lb/> hearers to courage and perseverance and to warn<lb/> them against despondency&#63;  You would probably say&#44;<lb/> &#8220;As long as your heart is good and your intentions<lb/> are pure&#44; you need not complain&#44; nor fear.<lb/>  The approbation of your conscience&#44; and the coun&#45;<lb/>tenance of the almighty&#44; will preserve your in&#45;<lb/>ward peace amidst the most <sic>harrassing</sic> occur&#45;<lb/>rences.  Vain&#44; hollow and thanging<add>&#63;</add> is the applause<lb/> of man.  Take it for what it is worth&#44; fret not<lb/> when it is withheld&#44; or bestowed on unworthy ob&#45;<lb/>jects.&#8221;  I am sure&#44; you would present the subject</p>
			<pb n="3"/>
				<p>in such a light&#44; and I am much mistaken&#44; if<lb/> you do not apply the same sentiments to your<lb/> own case.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">We are anxiously awaiting the Bible.  I<lb/> heard&#44; that it is finished.  Let us have it&#44; therefore<lb/> at your earliest convenience.  I hope the en&#45;<lb/><sic>terprize</sic> may be a profitable one&#44; as it richly<lb/> deserves to be.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Hoping that this may reach you in<lb/> your good health and spirits</p>
			<p rend="indent(5)">I remain</p>
			<p rend="indent(5)">yours truly</p>
			<p rend="indent(6)"><persName role="author">James K. Gutheim</persName></p>
		</body>
